Logistic Regression

In this homework, you will fit logistic regression classifiers to data. You will evaluate the quality of the model’s predictions by calculating the misclassification rate. You will plot the model’s ROC curve for all prediction thresholds, and calculate the auc. You will then use the performance function in the ROCR library to calculate an optimal threshold and evaluate the classification of the model using that threshold.

Next, you will fit another model on the data and add it’s ROC curve to the first model. You will compare the performance of these two models.

Finally, you will perform K-fold cross validation and report on the performance characteristics of your model.

The data comes from a study of factors relating to presence/absence of levee failure at sites on the Mississippi River.

Predicted label: failure 0=no, 1=yes

Predictors: river mile
Site underlain by coarse-grain channel fill (sediment) Borrow pit indicator Meander location (1=Inside bend, 2=outside bend, 3=chute, 4=straight) channel width floodway width constriction factor land cover type (1=open water, 2=grassy, 3=agricultural, 4=forest) vegetative buffer width channel sinuosity dredging intensity bank revetement

The data is found in the file “levee.csv”.

mod = glm(failure ~ .,data = train.data, family = binomial(logit))

Accuracy-based threshold

Q8 (5pts): Based on the ROC, calculate and display the “best”optimal" threshold (or thresholds) using the “performance” function. You will have to dig into the object returned to get the threshold (see the activity for an example).

acc <- performance(pred, "acc")
ac.val <- max(unlist(acc@y.values))
best.thresh <- unlist(acc@x.values)[unlist(acc@y.values) == ac.val]

Adding another model to the ROC curve

Now fit another model, call it model2, and compare its ROC curve to the original model, call it model1. Model2 will predict failure based on the following predictors: sediments, constriction, cover, sinuosity. Recall that the original model predicted failure from all predictors.

Q12 (15pts): Use the train.data and test.data you created in Q2. In a series of statements, re-fit model1, get its predictions, and write all statements to plot its ROC curve. Add the 50-50 diagonal, dotted line to the plot. Then, do the same for model2, except make its line dotted, and use the add=TRUE parameter to the call to plot to add the model2 curve to the existing plot.

model1<-glm(failure~.,data=train.data, family=binomial(logit))
model.predictions<-predict(model1, newdata=test.data, type="response")
pred<-prediction(model.predictions,true.labels)
perf<-performance(pred,'tpr','fpr')
plot(perf,main="ROC")
abline(0,1,lty=3)

model2<-glm(failure~sediments+constriction+cover+sinuosity, data=train.data, family=binomial)
model.predictions2<-predict(model2, test.data[,-1],type="response")
pred2<-prediction(model.predictions2,true.labels)
perf2<-performance(pred2,'tpr','fpr')

plot(perf2,lty=3,add=TRUE)

Cross validation

Q14 (15pts): Carry out a logistic regression analysis using 5-fold cross-validation. Fit model2 for each fold and calculate the misclassificaton rate as well as the AUC. These evaluation results are stored in vectors which are consolidated in a data frame after the loop has finished. At the end, you have five values for misclassification rate and AUC. Use 0.5 as the classification threshold.

set.seed(12345)

data.size = nrow(levee.df)
data.cols = ncol(levee.df)
num.folds = 5
 
levee.df["fold"] = floor(runif(data.size)*num.folds)+1
levee.df$fold = factor(levee.df$fold)
misclassification.rates = c()
auc = c()
class.threshold = 0.5
for(i in c(1:num.folds)){
   
    train = levee.df[(levee.df$fold!=i), 1:(data.cols)]
    test = levee.df[(levee.df$fold==i),1:(data.cols)]
    model.predictions = predict(model2, newdata = test[,-1], type="response")
    true.labels = test[,1]
    pred.labels = rep("No",length(true.labels))
    pred.labels[model.predictions>class.threshold]="Yes"
    pred.labels = factor(pred.labels)
    num.incorrect.labels = sum(pred.labels!=true.labels)
    misc.rate = num.incorrect.labels/length(pred.labels)
   
    misclassification.rates = c(misclassification.rates, misc.rate)
    pred = prediction(model.predictions,true.labels)
   
    perf.auc = performance(pred,'auc',fpr.stop=1)
    auc = c(auc, slot(perf.auc,"y.values")[[1]])
}

Q15 (5pts): Plot the misclassification results in a scatterplot, adding lines to connect the points. Title the plot: “Misclassification rates”, title the vertical axis: “misc”, and the horizontal axis: “folds”.

plot(misclassification.rates, type = "o", xlab="Fold", ylab="Misclassification Rate", main = "Misclassification Rate Per Fold")

Q16 (5pts): Plot the AUC results in a scatterplot, adding lines to connect the points. Title the plot: “Area under ROC curve”, title the vertical axis: “auc”, and the horizontal axis: “folds”.

plot(auc, type = "o", xlab="Fold", ylab="AUC", main = "Area Under ROC Curve")
